{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CnzPH3TfTkngibK1zZgL3t","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me create a detailed analysis report:\n\n## Log Streaming Architecture Analysis\n\nI've completed a thorough exploration of how step logs are handled during workflow execution in the Cloche system. Here's the comprehensive analysis:\n\n### 1. How the Agent Executes Workflow Steps and Captures Output\n\n**In-Container Agent (`cmd/cloche-agent/main.go`):**\n- The agent runs inside the container and reads workflow DSL files\n- Creates a unified log writer that writes to `.cloche/output/full.log`\n- Executes steps through an engine with status reporting\n\n**Step Execution (`internal/agent/runner.go`):**\n- For **script steps**: Uses `generic.Adapter` to execute shell commands via `exec.Command`\n  - Captures combined output via `CombinedOutput()`\n  - Writes output to `.cloche/output/<step-name>.log`\n- For **agent steps** (LLM):\n  - Uses `prompt.Adapter` to execute Claude Code agent\n  - Can use either buffering or streaming mode depending on whether `StatusWriter` is set\n  - When streaming is enabled, reads stdout line-by-line and streams text through `StatusWriter`\n  - Writes full output to `.cloche/output/<step-name>.log`\n\n**Output Capture Patterns:**\n- All step output is written to per-step log files: `.cloche/output/<step-name>.log`\n- For agent steps, also creates `llm-<step-name>.log` copies for special handling\n- A unified log aggregates all output to `.cloche/output/full.log` with timestamps and type prefixes (`[type]`)\n\n### 2. How Logs Are Streamed Back from Container to Daemon\n\n**Container to Daemon Communication (`internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`):**\n\nThe `AttachOutput()` method streams container logs via:\n```go\ndocker logs -f <containerID>  // Uses -f flag for follow mode\n```\nThis creates a live stream of stdout that can be read in real-time.\n\n**Daemon Log Tracking (`internal/adapters/grpc/server.go` - `trackRun()`):**\n\nThe daemon:\n1. Attaches to container output via `AttachOutput(ctx, containerID)`\n2. Creates a `bufio.Scanner` to read lines from the stream\n3. Parses JSON-lines status messages from the agent:\n   - `MsgLog` - direct log lines (fast path, no store interaction)\n   - `MsgStepStarted` - records step start timestamps\n   - `MsgStepCompleted` - records step result and completion timestamp\n   - `MsgRunTitle` - captures run title from prompt\n   - `MsgRunCompleted` - marks run complete\n\n4. **For log messages specifically** (lines 202-210):\n   - Publishes directly to the `logBroadcast` broadcaster with type \"llm\"\n   - Does NOT interact with the database for logging\n   - Non-blocking publish: if subscriber buffer is full (256 items), logs are dropped for that subscriber\n\n**Post-Run Processing:**\n- After container exits, extracts step output files from container: `docker cp <container>:/workspace/.cloche/output/. <dst>`\n- Also captures full container logs: `docker logs <container>` → saved to `container.log`\n- Indexes all extracted log files in the log store (SQLite)\n\n### 3. How the CLI Displays Logs to the User\n\n**Multiple Log Serving Paths:**\n\n**gRPC Streaming (`StreamLogs` RPC):**\n- If step_name or log_type filters are specified: streams from log index (SQLite) or file paths\n- Otherwise, serves the full.log file if available\n- Falls back to per-step files\n\n**Web Dashboard (`internal/adapters/web/handler.go` - SSE streaming):**\n\n**Active Runs** (`handleAPIStream`):\n- Subscribes to live broadcaster with `logBroadcast.Subscribe(id)`\n- Streams log lines as Server-Sent Events (SSE) with JSON data\n- Each line is flushed immediately using `http.Flusher`\n- When run completes or subscriber unsubscribes, closes the stream\n\n**Completed Runs**:\n- Serves archived `full.log` file by reading it sequentially\n- Parses lines matching `[timestamp] [type] content` format\n- Converts each line to JSON and streams as SSE\n- For \"llm\" type lines, parses Claude stream JSON format and extracts human-readable text\n\n**CLI Log Polling (`cmd/cloche/poll.go`):**\n- Simple polling mechanism: calls `GetStatus` RPC every 2 seconds\n- Reports step start/completion events but does NOT stream detailed logs\n- Used for basic status monitoring, not detailed log output\n\n### 4. Where Buffering Might Prevent Real-Time Display\n\n**Multiple Buffering Points:**\n\n**1. JSON Encoder Buffering (Critical Issue)**\n   - **Location**: `internal/protocol/status.go` line 65\n   - The `StatusWriter` uses `json.NewEncoder(w)` which **internally buffers output**\n   - `json.Encoder.Encode()` doesn't flush after each write\n   - **Impact**: Status messages can be delayed by Go's internal buffering, potentially several kilobytes\n   - **No explicit flush**: The code never calls `Flush()` (which doesn't exist on encoders anyway)\n\n**2. bufio.Scanner Buffering in Daemon**\n   - **Location**: `internal/adapters/grpc/server.go` line 194\n   - Scanner buffers up to 256KB per scan (line 176 in prompt.go)\n   - Lines may accumulate before being processed and published to broadcaster\n\n**3. Broadcaster Buffer**\n   - **Location**: `internal/logstream/broadcaster.go` line 63\n   - Each subscriber has a 256-item buffered channel\n   - When full, new log lines are **silently dropped** (non-blocking publish, line 104-107)\n   - Slow consumers lose intermediate logs\n\n**4. HTTP Response Buffering**\n   - Web streaming properly flushes with `http.Flusher` after each SSE event\n   - But the data source (live broadcaster) can drop logs if subscribers are slow\n\n**5. Per-Step Output Buffering**\n   - In `prompt.Adapter.tryCommand()` (lines 158-200):\n     - Pipes stdout through scanner with buffer up to 256KB\n     - Lines are accumulated in `lineBuf` buffer\n     - Text extraction from Claude JSON stream happens gradually\n     - Only flushes to StatusWriter when a complete line forms\n     - **Partial lines may be buffered indefinitely** if output doesn't contain newlines\n\n**6. Unified Log File Buffering**\n   - `logstream.Writer` (lines 45-58):\n     - Uses `os.WriteFile()` which opens file in append mode\n     - Each `.Log()` call writes immediately but to OS file buffers\n     - File may not be synced to disk immediately\n     - **Not flushed until writer is closed** (line 61)\n\n### Critical Buffering Chain During Execution\n\nFor a typical LLM agent step, the buffering chain is:\n\n1. **Claude Code stdout** → (variable line endings)\n2. **bufio.Scanner** (256KB buffer) → JSON lines\n3. **Stream JSON parser** (prompt.go lines 182-200) → accumulates until newline\n4. **StatusWriter.Log()** via `json.Encoder` → **unbuffered write attempt to stdout**\n5. **Go runtime stdout buffer** → (typically line-buffered or full-buffered depending on context)\n6. **Docker logs capture** → bufio.Scanner (line 194 server.go) → 256KB default\n7. **Broadcaster** → 256-item channel per subscriber → **drops if full**\n8. **Web SSE stream** → properly flushed each line\n9. **Unified log file** → buffered until close\n\n### Key Files and Line Numbers\n\n| Component | File | Key Lines | Issue |\n|-----------|------|-----------|-------|\n| Agent status writer | `internal/protocol/status.go` | 35-66 | JSON encoder doesn't flush |\n| Prompt streaming | `internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go` | 158-217 | Line buffering, partial lines accumulate |\n| Daemon log tracking | `internal/adapters/grpc/server.go` | 182-251 | bufio.Scanner buffering |\n| Log broadcaster | `internal/logstream/broadcaster.go` | 63, 104-107 | Fixed 256-item buffer, drops on overflow |\n| Web streaming | `internal/adapters/web/handler.go` | 669-735 | **Properly flushes** each SSE event |\n| Unified log writer | `internal/logstream/logstream.go` | 20-66 | No explicit flush until Close() |\n| Docker logs | `internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go` | 165-177 | AttachOutput uses docker logs -f |\n\n### Summary\n\nThe real-time log display is prevented by **multiple layers of buffering**:\n\n1. **Primary culprit**: The JSON encoder in StatusWriter doesn't have an explicit flush mechanism\n2. **Secondary issue**: Line buffering in stream parsers waiting for newlines\n3. **Tertiary issue**: The broadcaster's fixed 256-item buffer drops logs if consumers are slow\n4. **Minor issues**: OS-level buffering on file writes and scanner buffers\n\nThe web dashboard properly streams logs when they're published, but the bottleneck is getting logs from the container to the broadcaster in real-time. The prompt adapter's streaming mode helps, but it still accumulates partial lines."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: abf926bad56e1ddbd (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 78753\ntool_uses: 34\nduration_ms: 51592</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b192fff1-2075-40cb-b513-cbbf26873af4","uuid":"a71e170e-d5a6-4412-964b-22928bc026d7","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the codebase to understand how step logs are currently handled during workflow execution. I need to understand:\n\n1. How the agent executes workflow steps and captures output\n2. How logs are streamed back from the container to the daemon\n3. How the CLI displays logs to the user\n4. Where buffering might be happening that prevents real-time log display\n\nKey areas to explore:\n- cmd/cloche-agent/ - the in-container agent\n- internal/adapters/ - especially agent adapters and gRPC\n- internal/ports/ - interfaces for streaming/logging\n- cmd/cloche/ and cmd/cloched/ - CLI and daemon log handling\n- Any proto files for gRPC streaming\n- Any files related to output capture or log streaming\n\nBe very thorough - look at all relevant files for log streaming, output capture, and status reporting.","agentId":"abf926bad56e1ddbd","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! Now I have a comprehensive under